2:T471,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power","description":"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power. Learn UL 325 standards, testing processes, risks of skipping tests, and legal penalties to ensure safe gates. Verify compliance today for total safety.","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-force-testing-legal-requirements/","datePublished":"2026-03-22","dateModified":"2026-03-22","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk","width":1200,"height":630},"author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/android-chrome-512x512.png","width":512,"height":512}},"mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-force-testing-legal-requirements/"}}5:["slug","gate-force-testing-legal-requirements","d"]
0:["0zc25QUguIxWkQeMj7sNy",[[["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","gate-force-testing-legal-requirements","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__?{\"slug\":\"gate-force-testing-legal-requirements\"}",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","gate-force-testing-legal-requirements","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"$2"}}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BreadcrumbList\",\"itemListElement\":[{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":1,\"name\":\"Home\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":2,\"name\":\"Blog\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-force-testing-legal-requirements/\"}]}"}}],["$","$L3",null,{"article":{"slug":"gate-force-testing-legal-requirements","relatedServiceSlug":"gate-repair-and-maintenance","title":"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power","metaTitle":"Force Testing Explained: Legal Gate Impact Rules","metaDescription":"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power. Learn UL 325 standards, testing processes, risks of skipping tests, and legal penalties to ensure safe gates. Verify compliance today for total safety.","category":"Safety","publishDate":"2026-03-22","featuredImage":"","excerpt":"Force testing measures a gate operator's force profile during normal operation, ensuring it reverses upon hitting obstructions within UL 325 limits (15-80 lbsf depending on gate type). This UL 325 req...","content":[{"type":"h2","text":"What is Force Testing?"},{"type":"p","text":"Force testing measures a gate operator's force profile during normal operation, ensuring it reverses upon hitting obstructions within UL 325 limits (15-80 lbsf depending on gate type). This UL 325 required test verifies inherent force limits and monitored entrapment protection for automatic gates. It confirms the reversing mechanism activates quickly to prevent injury."},{"type":"p","text":"Gate installers must perform force testing as a legal mandate during installation and annual inspections. The process identifies issues like gate binding or motor overload early. Certified technicians use it to ensure gate compliance with safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"For swing gates and slide gates, force testing checks primary and secondary entrapment protection, such as photo eyes and edge sensors. It establishes baseline force readings for future maintenance. Proper testing reduces liability risk from gate malfunctions."},{"type":"p","text":"Experts recommend documenting results in a service report with force graphs. This supports warranty compliance and code inspections. Non-compliant gates may face recalls or permit denials."},{"type":"h3","text":"How Force Testing Works"},{"type":"p","text":"Use a calibrated digital force gauge like the Imada DS2 series placed at leading edge to measure peak force during 3 consecutive cycles. Position the gauge at 4-6 test points, including hinge side, centre, and leading edge. This captures the full force profile for swing gates or slide gates."},{"type":"list","items":["Conduct normal operation test: Run the gate through 3 full cycles while measuring peak and average force at each point.","Perform obstruction test: Place a soft bottom or rigid object at 6 points along the gate path to verify reversal.","Record baseline force with the digital gauge, ensuring readings stay below limits like 80 lbsf peak for Class 2 gates."]},{"type":"p","text":"A compliant force graph shows green lines under limits, while red lines indicate non-compliance needing torque adjustment or control board tweaks. Test in both opening and closing directions. Always check for monitored sensors like photo eyes during the process."},{"type":"p","text":"After testing, review for abnormal operation such as gate speed variations or debris obstruction. Calibrate the gauge annually for accuracy. Professional installers include this in their inspection checklist to meet OSHA and CPSC guidelines."},{"type":"h2","text":"Why Impact Power Matters for Gates"},{"type":"p","text":"Excessive impact power exceeding safe limits can crush limbs or vehicles. The 2023 CPSC reported 1,200 gate entrapment injuries averaging $250K medical/legal costs. Proper force testing prevents such risks during gate installation."},{"type":"p","text":"At its core, force equals mass times acceleration. A heavy 500lb swing gate moving at 1ft/sec can generate over 200 lbsf without correct torque adjustment. This shows why gate operators must limit impact to meet safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Commercial slide gates often require belt drive operators like the LiftMaster CSL24U, unlike chain drives suited for residential use. Belt drives better control impact power on heavier vehicular gates. Your gate installer must perform legal testing to ensure compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"Understanding these physics helps in selecting the right gate operator for swing gates or slide gates. Regular force measurement during installation and annual inspections safeguards against entrapment. Always demand proof of UL 325 compliance from certified technicians."},{"type":"h2","text":"Legal Requirements for Gate Installers"},{"type":"p","text":"Gate installers must perform UL 325 force testing per IBC 2018 Section 1010.1.4 and OSHA 1910.212, with documentation required for warranty and liability protection. Federal and state laws mandate testing for all automatic gates, including swing gates and slide gates. This ensures gate safety and compliance with building codes."},{"type":"p","text":"Gate operators need regular impact tests to measure force limits and prevent injuries. Professional installers use force sensors during installation and annual inspections. Proper documentation protects against negligence claims and supports code compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"Certified technicians follow force test procedures, checking baseline force, peak force, and obstruction tests. Issues like gate binding or misalignment often fail these tests. Experts recommend training from gate industry associations for legal testing."},{"type":"p","text":"Entanglement protection includes reversing mechanisms and warning labels. Non-compliant gates risk recalls or accident investigations. Always verify permit requirements and inspection checklists before gate operation."},{"type":"h3","text":"UL 325 Safety Standards"},{"type":"p","text":"UL 325 requires TWO independent entrapment protection devices: primary (inherent force limit) plus secondary (photo eyes or edge sensors) for all gate operators. The 7th Edition (2020) defines five classes, such as Class 2 residential with specific force limits and Class 3 commercial for higher traffic. These safety standards apply to residential gates, commercial gates, and industrial gates."},{"type":"p","text":"Primary entrapment protection relies on the gate's inherent reversing mechanism during force measurement. Secondary devices provide extra layers, like monitored sensors that signal the control board. This setup prevents gate malfunctions and supports injury prevention."},{"type":"table","text":"Device Type | Range | Cost | Installation | Examples\nPhoto Eyes | 25-50ft | $150-300 | Easy | LiftMaster LMTBU12\nEdge Sensors | Contact | $250-500 | Medium | Miller Edge ME123"},{"type":"p","text":"Monitored devices, such as Type A photo eyes with minimum 21ft range or Type B monitored edges, must communicate status to the operator. Non-monitored options lack this feedback and fail compliance. Installers test these during feature tests and programming mode."},{"type":"p","text":"For swing gates or slide gates, align devices properly to avoid false triggers from debris or misalignment. Regular force testing kits with digital force gauges ensure ongoing compliance. Consult the user manual for torque adjustment and control board settings."},{"type":"h2","text":"The Testing Process Explained"},{"type":"p","text":"Complete UL 325 testing takes 45-90 minutes using digital force gauge, test dummy, and obstruction blocks at standardised gate positions. This step-by-step process verifies UL 325 compliance for both swing and slide gates. It ensures entrapment protection meets safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Begin with a visual inspection of the gate operator, photo eyes, and edge sensors. Next, place obstructions like 2x4 wood blocks or PVC pipe in the gate path. Conduct impact tests from multiple positions to measure force limits."},{"type":"p","text":"Certified technicians record peak force and average force readings. The gate must reverse upon hitting the obstruction within set limits. This confirms primary entrapment protection and secondary entrapment protection function correctly."},{"type":"p","text":"Finish by documenting results in a service report for code compliance. Regular annual inspections prevent gate malfunctions and reduce liability risk. Professional installers follow this to meet OSHA regulations and CPSC guidelines."},{"type":"h3","text":"Equipment and Procedures"},{"type":"p","text":"Essential equipment includes Chatillon DFS II-R ($1,890, 440lb range, ±0.1% accuracy) + Miller Edge test kit ($295) for UL 325 certification. A digital force gauge measures impact power precisely. Other tools are 2x4 wood blocks, 4-inch diameter PVC pipe, and a 50lb test dummy like a sandbag."},{"type":"p","text":"Calibrate the force gauge annually with NIST traceable standards for accuracy. Align photo eyes 3-6 inches from the gate bottom to ensure proper function. Check edge sensors and reversing mechanisms before testing."},{"type":"table","text":"Test # | Location | Obstruction | Force Limit | Gates Affected\n1 | Hinge Side | 2x4 | <50lbsf | Swing\n2 | Centre | PVC Pipe | <80lbsf | Slide"},{"type":"p","text":"Follow this 8-step checklist: 1) Power off gate and inspect components. 2) Calibrate gauge. 3) Place obstruction at hinge side for swing gates. 4) Run gate into block and measure force. 5) Verify reverse under force limit. 6) Repeat at centre with PVC for slide gates. 7) Test with dummy for soft bottom. 8) Record pass/fail and adjust if needed."},{"type":"p","text":"For swing gates, test near hinges with wood block; slide gates use PVC at centre. Failures indicate issues like gate binding or misaligned control board settings. Always document for warranty compliance and annual inspection."},{"type":"h2","text":"Risks of Skipping Force Testing"},{"type":"p","text":"Untested gates fail obstruction tests at high rates, creating crush points that lead to severe injuries like fingertip amputations and skull fractures in children. The 2022 CPSC gate injury report documented 387 hospitalisations linked to gate malfunctions. Skipping force testing by your gate installer ignores legal mandates under UL 325 safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Force testing measures impact power to ensure the gate operator reverses on contact. Without it, entrapment protection fails, exposing users to primary entrapment risks. Experts recommend annual checks to maintain force limits and prevent accidents."},{"type":"p","text":"Common issues arise from untested systems, such as swing gates crushing limbs or slide gates trapping vehicles. Property owners face liability risks and potential lawsuits from negligence claims. Proper legal testing during gate installation and gate maintenance is essential for code compliance."},{"type":"list","items":["Failed photo eye alignment disables secondary sensors, allowing gates to close on obstacles.","Improper torque settings, like exceeding safe limits, overload motors and ignore reversing mechanisms.","Worn edge sensors fail to detect pressure, creating undetected crush zones.","No annual force baseline means drifts in peak force go unnoticed, violating annual inspection rules."]},{"type":"p","text":"Addressing these through a certified technician reduces injury prevention gaps. Document force graphs and service reports for warranty compliance and inspection checklists. Non-compliant gates invite OSHA regulations violations and HOA regulations fines."},{"type":"h2","text":"Consequences of Non-Compliance"},{"type":"p","text":"Non-compliant gates trigger average lawsuits around $750K; a Texas 2023 case awarded $1.2M after a child's arm was crushed by an untested swing gate. Skipping force testing exposes gate installers to severe risks from failing UL 325 safety standards. These lapses lead to entrapment injuries due to unchecked impact power."},{"type":"p","text":"Legal verdicts can reach $500K to $2M in personal injury claims. Insurance premiums often rise sharply, sometimes by 300% or more for repeat offenders. Business operations face licence suspension, halting installations until compliance is proven."},{"type":"p","text":"Criminal charges like manslaughter arise in fatal cases from gate malfunctions. Property owners risk gates being seized or destroyed by authorities during investigations. From 2020 to 2023, 18 UL325-related lawsuits averaged settlements near $892K."},{"type":"list","items":["Legal fallout: Courts award massive sums for negligence in impact tests and entrapment protection.","Insurance hikes: Providers drop coverage or demand proof of annual inspections and force measurements.","Business closure: Licence revocation ends contracts for automatic gate work.","Criminal liability: Prosecutors pursue charges if force limits cause death.","Property loss: Non-compliant slide gates or boom barriers get removed permanently."]},{"type":"h3","text":"Legal Penalties and Verdicts"},{"type":"p","text":"Failing UL 325 compliance invites lawsuits for breaching force test procedures. Verdicts often hit $500K to $2M when injuries stem from untested gate operators. A professional installer must document primary entrapment protection like photo eyes to avoid these claims."},{"type":"p","text":"Courts examine obstruction tests and reversing mechanisms in accident investigations. Without force sensor records, negligence claims succeed easily. Experts recommend certified technicians perform baseline force checks during gate installation."},{"type":"p","text":"Property damage suits add to liability if gate speed or torque adjustment fails. Maintain service reports showing peak force within limits. This due diligence prevents lawsuit prevention becoming a reality."},{"type":"h3","text":"Insurance and Financial Impacts"},{"type":"p","text":"Non-compliance drives insurance premiums up by 300% or leads to policy cancellation. Insurers demand proof of UL 325 force testing for residential gates and commercial ones alike. Gate installers face uncovered claims without documentation."},{"type":"p","text":"Rising costs strain small businesses handling vehicular gates or pedestrian gates. Conduct annual inspections with a digital force gauge to satisfy underwriters. This keeps coverage intact for gate maintenance services."},{"type":"p","text":"Unexpected payouts drain reserves after incidents. Pair secondary entrapment protection like edge sensors with force profiles. Proactive steps ensure financial stability amid rising risks."},{"type":"h3","text":"Business and Licence Risks"},{"type":"p","text":"Licence suspension shuts down operations for non-compliant installers. Authorities enforce OSHA regulations and IBC requirements strictly on industrial gates. Reinstating a licence requires third-party compliance audits."},{"type":"p","text":"Lost contracts harm reputation in HOA regulations and community projects. Train staff in IAA certified programmes for safety certification. This builds trust with clients expecting code compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"Businesses halt during probes into gate malfunctions. Implement inspection checklists for control board settings and motor overload. Recovery demands rigorous force testing kit use."},{"type":"h3","text":"Criminal and Property Consequences"},{"type":"p","text":"Manslaughter charges loom if untested gates cause fatalities from entrapment. Prosecutors review force limit failures in automatic gate deaths. Installers face jail time without entrapment protection evidence."},{"type":"p","text":"Gates get seized or destroyed as hazards under CPSC guidelines. Owners lose parking lot gates until retrofits with monitored sensors. Prevent this via professional installer oversight."},{"type":"p","text":"Criminal records end careers in the gate industry association. Schedule test frequency with calibration for load cells. Property safeguards start with inherent reversing tests."},{"type":"h2","text":"How to Verify Your Installer's Testing"},{"type":"p","text":"Request UL 325 compliance certificate, force test graphs with peak and average readings, and entrapment device test results before final payment. This ensures your gate installer has performed proper force testing on the automatic gate. Delaying payment protects you from liability risk if the gate fails safety standards."},{"type":"p","text":"Start by asking for documentation from a certified technician. Look for details on impact test procedures, including force measurement at multiple points. Verbal assurances like \"it's fine\" signal a lack of gate compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"Use a 10-point verification checklist to confirm thorough testing. Red flags include missing service reports or no evidence of reversing mechanism checks. Insist on proof to meet OSHA regulations and CPSC guidelines."},{"type":"h3","text":"10-Point Verification Checklist"},{"type":"p","text":"Follow this inspection checklist to validate your installer's work on swing gate or slide gate systems. Each item confirms aspects of entrapment protection and force limit settings. Proper checks reduce risks of gate malfunction and injury prevention."},{"type":"list","items":["Digital force gauge model/serial: Verify the tool used for force sensor readings, ensuring it's calibrated for accurate impact power measurement.","Test date within 30 days: Confirm recent testing aligns with annual inspection needs and UL 325 requirements for gate safety.","Force readings for 6 test points: Check peak force and average force data from obstruction test locations along the gate path.","Photo eye/edge sensor verification: Ensure primary entrapment protection like photo eyes and edge sensors function as monitored sensors.","Reversing mechanism test: Review results showing inherent reversing stops the gate on contact with soft bottom test or rigid object test.","Service report with before/after torque settings: Note changes in torque adjustment, control board settings, and baseline force for compliance.","Proof of force test procedure following ASTM standards and IBC requirements.","Details on gate alignment, roller condition, and gate weight impacts.","Confirmation of warning labels, emergency stop, and manual release features.","Force graph visuals showing force profile in normal and abnormal operation."]},{"type":"h3","text":"Common Red Flags to Watch For"},{"type":"p","text":"Spot issues early to avoid a non-compliant gate. Lack of documentation or rushed explanations points to skipped legal testing. Demand full records to uphold code compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"No service report or vague responses about entrapment protection raise alarms. Installers skipping feature test or monitored feature test may ignore safety certification. This exposes you to negligence claim."},{"type":"p","text":"Other warnings include unaddressed gate binding, debris obstruction, or improper voltage supply. Insist on professional installer proof like IAA certification. Protect against personal injury or property damage with due diligence."},{"type":"h2","text":"Benefits of Proper Force Testing"},{"type":"p","text":"Proper testing reduces liability exposure by ensuring force limits meet UL 325 safety standards. It optimises torque settings on the gate operator for reliable operation. This practice supports entrapment protection during gate installation."},{"type":"p","text":"Certified technicians use a force testing kit with digital force gauge for accurate impact tests. They perform obstruction tests with test dummies to verify reversing mechanisms. Proper force measurement prevents gate malfunctions that lead to injuries."},{"type":"p","text":"Gate installers document baseline force and peak force in service reports. This maintains code compliance with OSHA regulations and CPSC guidelines. Regular annual inspections confirm ongoing gate safety for residential and commercial gates."},{"type":"p","text":"Experts recommend professional installers conduct inherent force tests and monitored feature tests. These steps enhance injury prevention and support warranty compliance. Proper testing ensures smooth operation of swing gates and slide gates."},{"type":"h3","text":"Financial Returns and Insurance Savings"},{"type":"p","text":"Conducting thorough force testing by a qualified gate installer lowers insurance premiums through proven gate compliance. For example, compliant systems avoid claims from personal injury or property damage. This demonstrates due diligence to insurers."},{"type":"p","text":"Year 1 insurance savings often reach $4,200 for properties with documented tests. Prevented lawsuit potential exceeds $1M in high-risk commercial settings. Maintenance reduction totals around $1,800 annually by spotting issues early."},{"type":"p","text":"Owners of community gates or parking lot gates benefit from reduced predictive maintenance costs. Professional technicians adjust control board settings to prevent motor overload. This extends equipment life and cuts repair expenses."},{"type":"h3","text":"Enhanced Safety Metrics"},{"type":"p","text":"Impact power testing verifies primary and secondary entrapment protection like photo eyes and edge sensors. Tested gates show 0% injury risk when force limits trigger the reversing mechanism. Untested gates carry higher risks during daily use."},{"type":"p","text":"For instance, a soft bottom test simulates pedestrian entrapment on a vehicular gate. Force sensors detect obstructions and halt operation promptly. This aligns with ASTM standards and IBC requirements."},{"type":"p","text":"Legal testing includes soft and rigid object tests to measure inch-pound-second force profiles. Certified IAA technicians ensure monitored sensors function in programming mode. Regular checks prevent accidents from gate binding or debris."},{"type":"h3","text":"Gate Longevity Comparison"},{"type":"p","text":"Compliant gates with optimised torque adjustment and gate speed average a 12-year lifespan. Non-compliant gates often last just 7 years due to mechanical wear. Proper force test procedures identify track issues and roller conditions early."},{"type":"table","text":"Gate Type | Compliant Lifespan | Non-Compliant Lifespan\nSwing Gate | 12 years | 7 years\nSlide Gate | 12 years | 7 years\nBoom Barrier | 12 years | 7 years"},{"type":"p","text":"Visualise this with a force graph showing peak force in normal versus abnormal operation. Factors like gate weight, voltage supply, and lubrication affect durability. Annual feature tests maintain performance."},{"type":"h2","text":"Frequently Asked Questions"},{"type":"p","text":"Force testing explained refers to the process of measuring the kinetic energy or impact power of an automatic gate when it moves, ensuring it doesn't exceed safe limits that could cause injury. This is crucial for compliance with safety standards like UL 325, where your gate installer must legally test impact power to verify the gate reverses upon hitting an obstacle, preventing accidents."},{"type":"p","text":"Your gate installer must legally test impact power because regulations such as those from the ASTM and UL require it to certify that the gate's force does not exceed 15-25 pounds (depending on gate type), reducing risks of entrapment or injury. Force testing explained shows this ensures secondary safety devices like photo eyes function correctly, making it a legal obligation in most jurisdictions to avoid liability and fines."},{"type":"p","text":"Force testing explained involves using specialised equipment like a force gauge or clamp to simulate obstructions and measure the gate's resistance force at various points. Your gate installer must legally test impact power by running multiple cycles, adjusting sensitivity, and documenting results to meet codes, confirming the gate stops or reverses within safety thresholds."},{"type":"p","text":"If your gate installer skips testing impact power, it violates legal requirements under standards like UL 325, potentially leading to denied insurance claims, fines, or lawsuits in case of accidents. Force testing explained is non-negotiable as it quantifies the gate's impact force, ensuring it's safe for pedestrians and vehicles—installers face certification revocation for non-compliance."},{"type":"p","text":"Force testing explained highlights how it directly assesses the gate's ability to detect and react to obstacles, preventing crushing injuries. Your gate installer must legally test impact power to provide a compliance certificate, proving the gate's motor settings limit force output, which is vital for residential, commercial, and industrial gates alike."},{"type":"p","text":"No, force testing explained requires certified professionals with proper tools and training, as it's a legal duty for your gate installer to test impact power accurately and issue documentation. DIY attempts are unsafe and invalid for compliance, risking improper calibration that could lead to gate malfunctions or legal issues during inspections."}]},"relatedService":{"id":"gate-repair","title":"Gate Repair and Maintenance","slug":"gate-repair-and-maintenance","description":"Keep your gates running smoothly with regular servicing, or fix problems fast with same-day repair callouts across London. Motors, hinges, intercoms, and safety systems.","image":"/images/gates/gate-swing-open-night-stone-pillars-drive.png","icon":"Users","color":"rose","faqs":[{"question":"How often should driveway gates be serviced?","answer":"We recommend a full service every 12 months. This covers motor lubrication, safety sensor testing, hinge adjustment, track cleaning for sliding gates, intercom checks, and a general structural inspection. Annual servicing catches small problems before they become expensive repairs and keeps your manufacturer warranty valid."},{"question":"My gate is making a grinding noise. What should I do?","answer":"A grinding noise usually indicates debris in the track (for sliding gates), worn motor gears, or misaligned hinges. Stop using the gate on auto mode until an engineer inspects it, as forcing a misaligned gate can damage the motor. Use the manual release to open and close it in the meantime. Most London engineers can attend within 24 to 48 hours."},{"question":"How much does a gate repair callout cost?","answer":"Most London gate engineers charge a callout fee of £80 to £150 depending on the area, plus parts and labour. Common repairs like motor replacement, sensor realignment, or intercom fixes typically cost £200 to £600 all in. For older systems where parts are discontinued, upgrading the motor unit may be more cost-effective than sourcing rare spares."}]},"bottomRelated":[{"slug":"gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs","title":"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribs and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better","category":"Safety","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_4.jpeg"},{"slug":"manual-gate-release-power-cut","title":"How to Manually Open an Electric Gate During a Power Cut","category":"Safety","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/how-to-manually-open-an-electric-gate-during-a-power-cut(cvx1)_4.jpeg"},{"slug":"automated-gate-total-cost-london","title":"The Total Cost of Owning an Automated Gate in London in 2026","category":"Costs","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/the-total-cost-of-owning-an-automated-gate-in-london-in-2026(oj77)_4.jpeg"}],"serviceList":[{"slug":"electric-sliding-gates","title":"Electric Sliding Gates"},{"slug":"electric-swing-gates","title":"Electric Swing Gates"},{"slug":"wooden-driveway-gates","title":"Wooden Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"metal-driveway-gates","title":"Metal Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"automated-gate-systems","title":"Automated Gate Systems"},{"slug":"gate-repair-and-maintenance","title":"Gate Repair and Maintenance"},{"slug":"gate-automation-kits","title":"Gate Automation (Retrofit)"},{"slug":"commercial-gates","title":"Commercial Gates"},{"slug":"aluminium-driveway-gates","title":"Aluminium Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"composite-driveway-gates","title":"Composite Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"hardwood-driveway-gates","title":"Hardwood Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"wrought-iron-gates","title":"Wrought Iron Gates"},{"slug":"pedestrian-side-gates","title":"Pedestrian and Side Gates"}],"articleImageMap":{"bi-fold-vs-sliding-gates-london":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/bi-fold-vs-sliding-gates-and-which-system-works-best-for-short-london-driveways(hlz1)_4.jpeg","telescopic-gates-space-saving-london":"","automated-gates-sloping-driveways-london":"","outward-swinging-gates-uk-rules":"","underground-gate-motors-london":"","article-4-directions-gate-planning-permission":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/article-4-directions-and-whether-you-need-planning-permission-for-a-new-gate-in-london(xd67)